subCards.title: Vaughan lauds Joe Root's 'common sense ball' after batter hits fifty in Ranchi
subCards.abstract: India vs England: Former England batter Michael Vaughan lauded Joe Root for his first fifty in the series. Root did not employ Bazball in the fourth Test match at Ranchi and patiently scored his half-century in 108 balls.

images.title: Vaughan lauds Joe Root's 'common sense ball' after batter hits fifty in Ranchi
images.caption: Vaughan lauds Joe Root's 'common sense ball' after batter hits fifty in Ranchi

highlights.text: The article reports on ***Joe Root's*** first *fifty* in the **Test series** between **England and India** in Ranchi. Root scored his fifty in *108 balls*, showing *patience* and *careful shots* after England's early collapse. He helped England reach *150* after losing their first five wickets, and continued to bat with *Ben Foakes* to post *180* for five at stumps on Day 1. Former England cricketer **Michael Vaughan** praised Root's approach and called it a *'common sense ball'* instead of *'Bazball'*, referring to Root's previous aggressive style that backfired in the third Test in Rajkot.

subCards.title: These Are the 11 Rarest Cat Colors and Patterns
subCards.abstract: The coolest rare cat colors Cats are intelligent and spunky creatures, forever keeping owners on their toes with their shenanigans. Along with an array of quirky cat behaviors and catlike charms, kitties also sport a variety of fur colors and patterns. Some of them are quite common, while others are considered rare cat colors. "Cats have a combinat...

images.title: Close Up Of Cats In A Row Eating
images.caption: Close-Up Of Cats In A Row Eating

highlights.text:
The article explains the ***rarest cat colors and patterns*** and their genetic and physical characteristics. It covers:

- **Cream**, a buff hue derived from red or ginger coloring with yellow pigment granules, seen in Persian, Ragdoll, Maine Coon, and other breeds.
- **Lilac**, a pale brown color with a slight purple tint, found in Persian, Siamese, Balinese, and Oriental Shorthair breeds.
- **Fawn**, a diluted coat color caused by the cinnamon gene, seen in Abyssinian, Oriental Shorthair, and British Shorthair breeds.
- **Colorpoint**, a pattern of lighter body color and darker markings around ears, paws, and nose, seen in Siamese, Himalayan, Birman, Ragdoll, and other breeds.
- **Tortoiseshell**, a mixture of orange and black fur, almost always female, seen in Maine Coon, Ragdoll, Persian, and other breeds.
- **Chocolate**, a combination of brown and black, sometimes resembling a Labrador retriever, seen in Havana Brown, Burmese, Balinese, Siamese, and other breeds.
- **Blue**, a rare color in real life and in cat pictures, thought to originate in Russia, seen in Russian Blue, Korat, Chartreux, Nebelung, and other breeds.
- **Black Smoke**, a dark smokey hue with black, gray, and white fur, often with different-colored paws, seen in Maine Coon, Norwegian Forest Cat, Turkish Angora, Siberian, and other breeds.
- **Chinchilla**, a faded look at the base of the hair with primary colors at the tips, seen in Persian and Maine Coon breeds.
- **Rosette**, a fusion of brown, black, and white spots, seen in Bengal, Serengeti, Savannah, Ocicat, and other breeds.
- **Albino**, a complete absence of coloring, affecting fur, eyes, and skin, seen in any cat breed.

subCards.abstract: The jury said that LaPierre had already repaid the NRA a little more than $1 million, and a judge will ultimately decide how much he must pay the group. It also found that former NRA treasurer and former CFO Wilson Phillips cost the organization $2 million through mismanagement.

images.caption: wayne lapierre, ex-nra chief, found liable in lawsuit over lavish spending, cost gun rights group $5.4 million

highlights.text:
**Jury verdict:** A New York state jury found that former NRA chief Wayne LaPierre and former treasurer Wilson Phillips mismanaged the gun rights group and cost it $7.4 million in total. LaPierre had already repaid $1 million to the NRA.

**Civil corruption case:** The lawsuit was filed in 2020 by New York Attorney General Letitia James, who accused the NRA of letting top executives divert millions of dollars for luxuries. The defense lawyers called the lawsuit a political "witch hunt".

**NRA's future:** James originally sought to dissolve the NRA, but the judge in 2022 said she had not shown sufficient public harm to justify a "corporate death penalty". The NRA has struggled in recent years, with revenue down 44% since 2016 and membership dropping by nearly one-third since 2018.

His reaction comes after users on the social media platform X posted Gemini AI responses regarding Prime Minister Narendra Modi and other well-known politica...

images.title: Google's AI chatbot Gemini violates India's IT laws: Rajeev Chandrasekhar

highlights.text: ***Rajeev Chandrasekhar***, the Union Minister of State for Electronics and Technology, **warned Google** about the **potential violation of Indian IT laws** by its **Gemini AI chatbot**. He cited the **Intermediary Rules (IT rules)** and the **Criminal code** as the sources of the violation. His warning came after users on **X** posted **Gemini AI responses** on **political figures** from India and other countries, which were deemed **malicious and woke** by the users. Google had earlier **paused the image generation feature** of Gemini AI due to **inaccuracies** in AI-generated **historical images** that depicted specific white figures as **people of colour**.

cards.title: PSL 2024: Hawk-Eye Issues Apology To PCB Following Mistake Which Costed Islamabad United A Loss Against Quetta Gladiator
cards.abstract: The fielding team and umpires were visibly in a state of shock after seeing the review of Rilee Rossouw.

images.title: PSL 2024: Hawk-Eye Issues Apology To PCB Following Mistake Which Costed Islamabad United A Loss Against Quetta Gladiator

highlights.text: The article reports on ***Hawk-Eye's*** error that **costed Islamabad United a loss** against Quetta Gladiators in the **Pakistan Super League (PSL) 2024**. The error occurred in the 11th over of the Gladiators' innings, when their captain *Rilee Rossouw* was wrongly adjudged out by umpire *Aleem Dar* after missing a sweep shot. The Gladiators requested a review and the Hawk-Eye showed that the ball hit Rossouw's pad outside the stumps, but also missed the wickets. The fielding team and umpires were **shocked** by the review outcome. Hawk-Eye **apologised** to the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) in a letter, acknowledging the error and explaining its cause. Islamabad skipper *Shadab Khan* criticized the technology and said it was a **match-changing moment** that should not happen in a big tournament. The Gladiators **chased down the target** of 139 with Rossouw unbeaten on 34.

cards.abstract: Karnataka government approved 'Karnataka Hindu Religious Institutions and Charitable Endowments Bill 2024' granting it the authority to impose taxes on temples generating revenues. The temples exceeding Rs 1 crore will be subject to a 10% tax while those with revenues ranging between Rs 10 lakh and Rs 1 crore will face a 5% tax levy. images.title: Row Erupts Over Karnataka's Tax On Temples With Revenue Over Rs 1 Cr

highlights.text: The article discusses the ***Karnataka Hindu Religious Institutions and Charitable Endowments Bill 2024***, which grants the state government the authority to **tax temples** based on their revenues. The bill specifies a **10% tax** for temples with revenues over **Rs 1 crore**, and a **5% tax** for those between **Rs 10 lakh and Rs 1 crore**. The bill sparked a **row** between the state's Chief Minister *Siddaramaiah* and BJP state unit chief *B Y Vijayendra*, who accused each other of being **anti-Hindu** and misleading the public. The bill's sponsor, Minister *Ramalinga Reddy*, defended the bill as a way to **support neglected temples** and urged the youth to **abandon their jobs** for political gain.

cards.title: 6 Best Bluetooth Speakers For Cars: For Music Lovers On The Go
cards.abstract: Best Bluetooth Speakers For Cars: The times when everything was wired are gone. With a lot of advancements in technology, everything has become easy to use with many hassles or difficulties. Bluetooth speakers have become an integral part of our lives and are now commonly used everywhere like, during parties, random jam sessions, or in cars while driving. With various brands available in the market we have made a list of the best Bluetooth...

highlights.text:
This web article presents the ***best Bluetooth speakers for cars*** for music lovers on the go. It reviews and recommends:

- **boAt Stone 180 5W Bluetooth Speaker**, with 10 hours of playtime, 800 mAh battery, and high-definition sound.
- **Zebronics ZEB-VITA Wireless 10W Portable Bar Speaker**, with 10W power, 5 hours of playback, USB Aux input, Micro SD card, and FM radio.
- **JBL Flip 5 Wireless Portable Bluetooth Speaker**, with 12 hours of playtime, PartyBoost mode, durable material, and IPX7-rated.
- **boAt Stone 352 Bluetooth Speaker**, with 10W of audio, TWS functionality, and 1800mAh battery.
- **Echo Dot (3rd Gen) - Smart speaker with Alexa**, compatible with most cars and offering various music services.
- **JBL Flip 6 Wireless Portable Bluetooth Speaker**, with 12 hours of playtime, wireless connection, and IP67-rated.

cards.title: Modern cities built on ancient ruins
cards.abstract: Did you know that some of the world's most modern cities are in fact among the most ancient? While their contemporary steel and glass veneer suggest a recent history, many of these cities are built on foundations that date back to antiquity. These historic building blocks have preserved a wealth of breathtaking monuments that provide a compelling contrast between the old and the new. So, what are the oldest newest cities on the planet? Click through and discover these fascinating urban destinations.

cards.title: 'Mind-blowing' deep sea expedition uncovers more than 100 never-before-seen species and a huge underwater mountain off the coast of Chile
cards.abstract: Scientists exploring the waters off the coast of Chile have discovered a huge underwater mountain that's home to a range of weird and wonderful creatures.

images.title: MailOnline logo
images.caption: MailOnline logo

highlights.text: Researchers from the ***Schmidt Ocean Institute*** have discovered a **huge underwater mountain** off the coast of Chile that hosts a diverse range of **new species**. They used an **underwater robot** to map **52,777 square kilometres** of the seafloor, finding **four new seamounts** with their own ecosystems. The tallest seamount, named **Solito**, is **3,530 metres** high, more than four times the height of the world's tallest building. The researchers captured images of **deep-sea corals, lobsters, squids, sponges, and other creatures** on the seamounts, some of which have not been seen before. The new species will be formally identified and added to the **Nippon Foundation – Nekton Ocean Census Program's** goal of finding **100,000 new marine species** in the next ten years.

cards.title: Kunal Kemmu admits he felt like hitting someone while watching Ranbir Kapoor's Animal: 'Munna Bhai 2 dekh ke Gandhigiri bhi sikh lo'
cards.abstract: Kunal Kemmu admitted even he felt like hitting someone while he was watching the Sandeep Reddy Vanga directorial Animal starring Ranbir Kapoor because this is the impact of cinema in evoking strong emotions. He urged viewers to become 'alpha' in the true sense by embracing non-violence and empathy.

images.title: Kunal Kemmu admits he felt like hitting someone while watching Ranbir Kapoor's Animal: 'Munna Bhai 2 dekh ke Gandhigiri bhi sikh lo'

highlights.text:
**Kunal Kemmu's views on alpha male heroes**: The actor questioned the glorification of violent and aggressive characters in films like Kabir Singh and Animal. He advised viewers to be sensible and empathetic, and not to take such portrayals seriously.

**Sandeep Reddy Vanga's success with Animal**: The director won the Best Director award for his film Animal, which starred Ranbir Kapoor and Bobby Deol. The film was a huge hit, earning Rs 900 crore worldwide. Bobby Deol also won the Best Actor in a Negative Role award for his role as Abrar.

slides.title: Plan a trip to Cairo and the Pyramids of Giza, Egypt
slides.body: There's lots going for the Egyptian capital in 2023. The much-anticipated Grand Egyptian Museum is scheduled to finally open its doors towards the end of the year and plenty of new luxury hotels are currently being built (with opening dates stretching into 2024). However, you may prefer to bed down on an eternally-desirable River Nile cruise, which stops at the Giza archaeological site just outside the city: as familiar as the awe-inspiring triangular silhouettes of the Pyramids of Giza seem, there’s nothing like seeing them with your own eyes.

slides.title: Peanut gallery
slides.body: The expression “no more comments from the peanut gallery” is often used to signify that the speaker has had enough of hecklers or unwelcome commentary. But it’s actually a Civil War-era racist expression referring to the cheapest seats in an auditorium, where cheap peanuts were sold as snacks and black people were required to sit.

image.title: Low-fat peanut butter
image.caption:
The fat that’s naturally found in peanut butter is healthy to consume, so it’s better if you stick to regular peanut butter rather than a low-fat version. To make up for the taste of reduced fat, companies often add more sugar or starchy fillers (things personal trainers try to avoid).

While on the topic of peanut butter, not all regular peanut butters are made with your health in mind. Many brands contain added sugars and oils, so it’s better to stick to more natural ones.

slides.title: Uppity
slides.body: These days many people seem to think the word “uppity” just indicates someone who’s snobby, but in fact it is a racist expression that was historically used by people in the southern U.S. to refer to a black person who didn’t know their place in society (which was considered to be below that of any white person).

cards.title: A 21-year-old had a stroke at graduation as a rare side effect of birth control. She wants people of all ages to know the signs and risk factors.
cards.abstract: When college athlete Marissa Fattore woke up feeling "off" on graduation day, she dismissed it as nerves. A few hours later, she had a stroke.

highlights.text:
**Stroke survivor**: Marissa Fattore, 21, had a stroke at her graduation ceremony. She had a blood clot in her brain that caused a rare form of stroke.

**Possible cause**: Doctors suspected that her estrogen birth control pill may have contributed to the stroke, as she had no other risk factors.

**Recovery**: Fattore spent a month in a physical rehabilitation center, where she learned to walk and talk again. She also adopted a healthy lifestyle to prevent future strokes.

**Warning signs**: Fattore wants people to know the acronym FAST, which stands for Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, and Time to call 911. Other symptoms include numbness, confusion, vision problems, and severe headache.
